{"key":"processedPost-15317254","value":{"id":15317254,"first":15317238,"last":15317444,"when":1320340626,"utime":"11/03/11 08:17 PM","content":"As has been said repeatedly around here by everyone but rank noobs, spraying the sides of a terrarium is a waste of time and water.&nbsp; It's the cakes themselves which need water, not the plastic which has no use for it whatsoever.<br />The mutations are normal, but those should have been picked days ago before the caps fully opened.<br />The small fruits are due to insufficient substrate moisture because you're spraying the walls instead of the cakes themselves.<br />Misting based on hygrometer reading is false reasoning.&nbsp; You don't mist to raise humidity except as a secondary benefit.&nbsp; The perlite is for creating humidity, and you mist the CAKES to replace moisture that has been lost due to giving proper fresh air exchange.&nbsp; When you mist the cakes, the overspray lands on the perlite, re-moistening it so it continues to provide humidity, while the holes provide for proper fresh air exchange.<br />RR","title":"Re: Help: Can you guys help me diagnose a mushroom problem? (pics)"}}